observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Local Chief Executive, through the Human Management Office:

 a. Establish specific and concrete policy guidelines relative to the hiring and rehiring of JO and CoS workers, including clear and equitable wage structure and monitoring and evaluation of services rendered. This is +in order to ensure not only the accomplishment of tasks that are aligned with the LGU’s objectives, but also to give to said workers what is due them based on their qualification and the task they perform;

b. Make available the installed biometrics system to the OJ/Cos workers and strictly monitor their DTR’s and accomplishments;

c. Maintain profile and identification of all JO and CoS workers.

We recommended that:

a. The Local Chief Executive require the Inventory Committee to formulate a revised Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) ensuring first completeness of records from the Accounting and Property Units which shall serve as inventory working papers;

b. The Local Chief Executive authorize, as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006, the committee members to be temporarily relieved of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same complete;

c. The Inventory Committee to carefully and completely execute the formulated Physical Inventory Plan to come up with and Inventory Report that contains all the necessary data/information that will facilitate reconciliation of records, and thus the cleansing of PPE accounts.

We recommended that the LCE:

a. Require all officials and employees to revisit Executive Order No. 77 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 on allowable transportation, miscellaneous, and Daily Travel Expenses to ensure that their respective preparation of the claims for travel expenses compliant with the existing guidelines;

b. Require the Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of supporting documents for claims of actual travelling and training expenses, and prudently examine and compute claims for travels such that only the proper and equitable amounts are granted to officials and employees;

c. Issue certifications of absolute necessity of excess claims for actual accommodation in accordance with EO 77, and authorize or approve such other claims which are consistent therewith, ensuring the judicious use of government funds.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:

Reconcile balances of Due to BIR, Due to GSIS, Due to Pag-IBIG and Due to PhilHealth accounts and effect the adjustments in the financial statements;

Consider the preparation and maintenance of individual subsidiary ledgers for all suppliers and employees to ensure accurate and reliable withholding and remittance of taxes, contributions, and loan amortizations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and other officers concerned to ensure that projects endorsed and implemented under the SBDP of NTF ELCAC are free from any issue on land/site to avoid adverse consequences. The Municipal Mayor should also direct:

The Municipal Engineer to require the contractors of subsequent infrastructure projects, including those under the same program herein, to comply with the appropriate size of signboards and the updating of the complete status and information therein;

The Municipal Engineer to ensure complete disclosure in the Inspection Report of the works accomplished and necessary rectifications, if any, to provide basis to the Local Chief Executive and the Municipal Accountant on the propriety of approval and processing of payments; 

The Municipal Accountant to present the lacking supporting documents; and

The local MENRO to coordinate with the EMB/DENR officials for the needed permit and clearance for the causeway project in order to complete the project.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, through the Human Resource Management Office:

Establish specific and concrete policy guidelines relative to the hiring and rehiring of JO and CoS workers, including clear and equitable wage structure and monitoring and evaluation of services rendered. This is in order to ensure not only the accomplishment of tasks that are aligned with the LGU’s objectives, but also to give to said workers what is due them based on their qualifications and the tasks they perform;

Make available the installed biometrics system to the JO/CoS workers and strictly monitor their DTRs and accomplishments;

Maintain profile and identification records of all JO and CoS workers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Inventory Committee to formulate a revised Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) ensuring first the completeness of records from the Accounting and Property Units which shall serve as inventory working papers;

The Local Chief Executive authorize, as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006, the committee members to be temporarily relieved of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed;

The Inventory Committee to carefully and completely execute the formulated Physical Inventory Plan to come up with and Inventory Report that contains all the necessary data/information that will facilitate reconciliation of records, and thus the cleansing of PPE accounts.

We recommended that the LCE:

a. Require all officials and employees to revisit Executive Order No. 77 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 on allowable transportation, miscellaneous, and Daily Travel Expenses to ensure that their respective preparation of the claims for travel expenses compliant with the existing guidelines;

b. Require the Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of supporting documents for claims of actual travelling and training expenses, and prudently examine and compute claims for travels such that only the proper and equitable amounts are granted to officials and employees;

c. Issue certifications of absolute necessity of excess claims for actual accommodation in accordance with EO 77, and authorize or approve such other claims which are consistent therewith, ensuring the judicious use of government funds.

We recommended that management:
1) Implement immediately the PPAs funded under the 20% DF of the current and prior years;
2) Henceforth implement within the timeline as scheduled in the AIP thru an  updated preparation of technical documents for the projects on the part of the MEO, and effective monitoring on the part of the MPDC, consistent with  the mandated responsibility of LGU officials, as embodied in the Joint DBM-DILG Memorandum Circular 2017-1;
3) Require the Budget Officer and Accountant to revert the unutilized balances of implemented or completed PPAs to the Unappropriated Surplus and/or recommend for its reappropriation  for other priority  PPAs. 
4) Appoint a permanent official that will head the MPDC apart from the MEO so that both offices may be able to exercise its mandated functions more effectively.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct immediate investigation of the non-existing/missing items of PPE to determine the persons accountable for such properties;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct a physical count of all Property, Plant and Equipment accounts;
Initiate the formulation of plans/strategies for the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking supporting documents;
Instruct the concerned officials responsible in the procurement process to ensure that the LGU only transact business with the legitimate suppliers/service providers.

We recommended that the LCE require:
The Local Finance Committee to prepare the reports showing the details of the utilization of the Bayanihan grant amounting to P11,018,387.00;
The BAC Secretariat to post the details of the awarded contracts in the GPPB Online Portal, as well as the accumulated reports on utilization of Bayanihan grant in at least three (3) conspicuous public places and submit the said reports or the information on the compliance to posting and reporting requirements to other offices where submission is required.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Disposal Committee to prepare the IIRUP and initiate the disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445 and COA Circular 92-386;
After the disposal, require the Disposal Committee to submit the necessary documents, as the basis of the latter to drop the unserviceable properties from the book of accounts in accordance with the existing accounting and auditing rules and regulations.

We recommended that the LCE require the LDRRM Officer:
To prepare the LDRRMF IP which includes PPAs chargeable from the prior year’s unexpended balance of the LDRRM Funds;
To prepare a revised/supplemental LDRRMF IP in case additional PPAs are authorized and such were not included the approved AIP;
To ensure the efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities is achieved.

We recommended that: 
a) The Accountant prepare adjusting journal entries to: 
i) reclassify the Construction in Progress - Infrastructure Asset of P11,841,215 to Road Net Work account; 
ii) close the Due to NGAs account of P11,866,215.80 in the Trust Fund and; 
iii) transfer the Road Network  account to the General Fund and record the corresponding Government Equity account   in order to reflect the correct balances of the accounts affected, and; 
b) Management return the unexpended/excess funds of P2,163,784.20 to the National Treasury.

We recommended that management: 

Fast track the implementation of the PPAs consistent with the MOAs for the benefit of the targeted constituents; 
Return to the Source Agency the balance of unutilized fund for completed projects in accordance with COA Circular No. 94-013 to enable the National government to re-appropriate the funds to other priority programs.

We recommended that the LCE through the Municipal Assessor:

take appropriate steps in order to attain 100% revision of all Tax Declarations of all RPUs in the municipality and submit the updated records to the Provincial Assessor as pre-requisite to the next General Revision and;
coordinate with the Provincial Assessor so that the 4th General Revision of Assessments and Property Classification be made as early as possible.

We recommend that:

a) The LSB convene to thresh out their concerns and problems  that are preventing performance of their duties and responsibilities;

b) The LSB  prepare the Annual SEF Budget following the procedure set forth in the Joint Circular and furnish the Local Accountant, Local Treasurer and Local Budget  Officer  a  copy of the budget;

c) The Local Accountant prepare the quarterly and annual report on SEF Utilization  using the format prescribed in the Joint Circular; 

Adhere to the Circular on the allowable expenses chargeable to SEF.
Furthermore, we recommend that the Local Chief Executive stop the practice of allowing reimbursement. Instead, payments should be made by check. Cash Advance should be granted to a Special Disbursing Officer who is under the administrative supervision of the LGU, and not to employees of DepEd.

